{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514916"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:28:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:28:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12405"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12405"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.6,0.06,0.03,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4913"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77775"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4913"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12405"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63291"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2228"},{"type":"tags","id":"2701"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8007"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8395"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42751"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43327"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44377"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44825"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77775"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old retired businessman is brought to the emergency department by his family with a three day history of fever and two days of productive cough, shortness of breath and diarrhoea. He is not oriented in time or space. His family report that they had a cruise trip to Tasmania a week ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is a non-smoker. His medical history includes ANCA vasculitis a year ago, for which he takes prednisolone and azathioprine as maintenance therapy. He does not have other medical illness. On examination his blood pressure is 98/60 mmHg, pulse 70/min, temperature 38.5\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, respiratory rate 20/min and SpO2 90% on room air. On auscultation there is bronchial breathing at the right base. A chest X-ray shows consolidation in the right lower and right middle lobes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the most likely causative organism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mycoplasma pneumoniae","Legionella pneumophila","Coxiella burnetii","Chlamydia pneumoniae","Burkholderia pseudomallei"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s current problem is pneumonia. Pneumonia can be classified into two groups, typical and atypical pneumonia, based on the causative organisms, clinical picture and imaging findings. Although in this case the sudden onset and clinical urgency point more towards a diagnosis of typical pneumonia, this can also occur in atypical pneumonia. Given the presence of extrapulmonary manifestations and recent travel history, atypical pneumonia should be included in the differential diagnoses. The most likely diagnosis in this case would be \u003Cstrong\u003ELegionnaires\u0027 disease\u003C/strong\u003E, which is caused by \u003Cem\u003ELegionella pneumophila\u003C/em\u003E, because of the presence of several risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough there is no pathognomonic symptom in \u003Cem\u003ELegionella \u003C/em\u003Einfection, it is more associated with gastrointestinal manifestations (particularly diarrhoea) than the other options. Relative bradycardia is also not uncommon in \u003Cem\u003ELegionella\u003C/em\u003E infection. The patient is immunosuppressed by continuous usage of prednisolone and azathioprine, which is a major risk factor of \u003Cem\u003ELegionella\u003C/em\u003E infection. His recent travel history is consistent with the exposure pattern as well. As a waterborne disease, Legionella is often transmitted via contamination of any water source. Cruise ships have complex water collection systems which generate aerosols, making them a hotbed for dissemination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cem\u003EM. pneumoniae \u003C/em\u003Eand\u003Cem\u003E Chlamydia pneumoniae \u003C/em\u003Eare also common causes of atypical pneumonia, they often cause milder symptoms and the risk profile in this case is more consistent with \u003Cem\u003ELegionella\u003C/em\u003E infection. \u003Cem\u003ECoxiella burnetii\u003C/em\u003E causes Q fever, which is a zoonotic disease characterised by contact with infected animal matter like faeces. \u003Cem\u003EBurkholderia pseudomallei \u003C/em\u003Ecauses melioidosis, which develops after contact with contaminated water and soil. This disease is rare worldwide, except for Southeast Asia and Northern Australia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Detailed history taking and identification of risk factors are important in determining the causative organism of atypical community acquired pneumonia","Immunocompromised individuals are much more susceptible to Legionella infection","Manmade reservoirs, hot tubs, aerosol-generating devices and places with water collection systems are all common sources of environmental exposure of Legionella spp."],"references":["Cunha BA, Burillo A, Bouza E. Legionnaires\u0027 disease. Lancet. 2016 Jan 23;387(10016):376-385. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(15)60078-2. Epub 2015 Jul 28. PMID: 26231463. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26231463/","Burillo A, Pedro-Botet ML, Bouza E. Microbiology and Epidemiology of Legionnaire\u0027s Disease. Infect Dis Clin North Am. 2017 Mar;31(1):7-27. doi: 10.1016/j.idc.2016.10.002. PMID: 28159177. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28159177/","Brady MF, Awosika AO, Nguyen AD, Sundareshan V. Legionnaires Disease. 2024 Feb 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28613558. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28613558/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63291"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12405"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63291","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63291"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T10:19:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T10:19:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4913"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77775"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},